 ⚙️ Common Firewall Tools in Linux
 1. iptables
- Legacy but powerful tool.  
- Works by defining chains of rules for incoming, outgoing, and forwarded traffic.  
- Example commands:  
  
   Block all incoming traffic by default
  sudo iptables -P INPUT DROP

   Allow SSH (port 22)
  sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

   Allow HTTP (port 80)
  sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT

 2. firewalld
- Modern, user-friendly alternative.  
- Uses zones (trusted, public, home, etc.) to group rules.  
- Example commands:  

   Start and enable firewalld
  sudo systemctl start firewalld
  sudo systemctl enable firewalld

   Allow SSH
  sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=ssh

   Allow HTTP
  sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=http
   Reload to apply changes
  sudo firewall-cmd --reload

Firewall Setup Commands in Linux
1. iptables (classic firewall tool)
Basic Setup
# Set default policies (deny everything by default)
sudo iptables -P INPUT DROP
sudo iptables -P FORWARD DROP
sudo iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT

# Allow loopback interface (localhost)
sudo iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT

# Allow established/related connections
sudo iptables -A INPUT -m conntrack --ctstate ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
Allow Common Services
# Allow SSH (port 22)
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

# Allow HTTP (port 80)
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT

# Allow HTTPS (port 443)
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT
Block Specific IP
# Block traffic from 192.168.1.100
sudo iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.1.100 -j DROP
Save Rules
# Save rules permanently (Debian/Ubuntu)
sudo iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4

# Save rules permanently (CentOS/RHEL)
sudo service iptables save

2. firewalld (modern zone-based firewall)
Start & Enable
sudo systemctl start firewalld
sudo systemctl enable firewalld
Allow Services
# Allow SSH
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=ssh

# Allow HTTP
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=http

# Allow HTTPS
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=https
Allow Ports
# Allow custom port (e.g., 8080/tcp)
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=8080/tcp
Block Services
# Remove SSH access
sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --remove-service=ssh
Reload Rules
sudo firewall-cmd --reload
List Rules
# List all active rules
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all
